  "texts": [
    "This interface can be represented by a function G: X → Q, where Q denotes the set of queries generated based on the context of X.",
    "The response from the API to a query q ∈ Q is denoted by R(q), where R: Q → Y maps queries to their responses.The integration process can be mathematically modeled as follows:Z = F(X, R(G(X)))(1)This process involved modifying the model's generation pipeline to include an additional step for query generation and response processing, which can be depicted by the following differential equation, where t represents the processing time:dP dt = λP(t) -µP(t)R(G(X))(2)Here, λ represents the rate of input text processing, and µ represents the modulation factor for integrating API responses, with P(t) denoting the progression of text generation over time.The integration was optimized to balance the use of realtime data with the model's pre-existing knowledge, aiming to enhance accuracy without compromising the speed and fluidity of text generation.",
    "This balance can be expressed by the optimization problem:max λ,µ α F(X, R(G(X)))dt -β λP(t) -µP(t)R(G(X)) dt(3) where α and β are weights reflecting the importance of accuracy and speed, respectively.Special attention was given to the ethical and privacy considerations of querying real-time internet data, implementing safeguards to ensure data privacy and compliance with data protection regulations.",
    "This aspect can be encapsulated by introducing a constraint C(R(G(X))) ≤ ϵ, where C measures the compliance level of the data usage with respect to privacy regulations, and ϵ is the acceptable threshold.",
    "Dataset and TrainingThe dataset employed for training and fine-tuning the integrated model was Google's BIG-Bench, which includes a diverse range of tasks designed to test various aspects of language models' capabilities [64]."
  ],
